Name: Abbeyhill Colony of Artists
Summary:
This community organisation, run by volunteers, provides a platform for exhibition to artists in any medium. Creatives who live in, or have a connection to, the Abbeyhill Colonies are welcome to take part.

Our aims are to promote artists’ work, bring the local residents together, nurture the community ethos and care for the long artistic heritage of the area.

Name: Albion Road Studios
Adress: Albion Business Centre, 78 Albion Rd, Edinburgh EH7 5QZ

Name: Art walk projects
Summary: The Art Walk Porty project is an artist-led project run by volunteers, that brings together local audiences and artists celebrating the public space and creative community of Portobello, Edinburgh's Seaside, culminating in an annual festival based around a walk. Our 2018 event worked with 80 artists over 52 locations. It started as a pilot project in 2015.

Name: Artlink
Summary: Artlink is an arts and disability organisation established in 1984. Artlink believes participation in the arts has an important role to play in realising personal and social change. Our aim is to increase opportunities to take part in the arts for those who experience disadvantage or disability in the East of Scotland. We offer practical support so people can get involved and work with venues to increase opportunities to enjoy the arts. Artlink establishes partnerships with artists, venues and organisations to help encourage positive change.

Name: Bare Branding
Summary: The beating heart of Bare Branding is our Bare Hub: a fully-equipped, open access studio space that allows users to produce their own signage, displays, custom imprinted products and many other branded items, all at extremely affordable rates. By paying a studio access fee users gain the use of our studio and one-on-one guidance on how to use the printers and cutters to produce professional results. From custom T-shirts to packaging, labels, posters, stickers and bags to museum-quality signage and displays. Everything is here to make your ideas into reality.

Name: Basic Mountain
Summary: A former 1850's dance studio, dwelling house, and at Fringe 2015 an arts venue that is testing a new model of residency for the festival by offering one company or individual artist the opportunity to locate themselves in Edinburgh for the whole of the festival to test new ideas and develop a programme of work for the city.

Name: Coburg House Studios
Summary: hub of artists, designers and makers in the heart of Edinburgh's Leith. We also have a on-site Shop and Gallery.

Name: Collective Gallery

Name: Craigmillar Community Arts

DOK is a non-profit contemporary artist run space that offered affordable studio and exhibition space to primarily
Scottish based artists although we also work with visual artists internationally.
Adress: The Steel Shed, Ocean Drive, Edinburgh EH6 6JJ

Name: Edinburgh Ceramics Workshop
Summary: Edinburgh ceramics workshop is a teaching pottery and open studio practice space dedicated to providing learning opportunities and practice space for people who are passionate about working with clay.

Name: Edinburgh College of Art
Adress: ECA Main Building and Hunter Building, 74 Lauriston Place, Edinburgh EH3 9DF

Name: Edinburgh contemporary Craft at techbase
Summary: Edinburgh Contemporary Crafts provides workshops and studio facilities in the disciplines of ceramics, jewellery, textiles, print and upholstery. As well as giving professionals a place to work, ECC runs a programme of courses which allows the public to access fully-equipped workshops and to be taught crafting skills by professional makers. The main ECC office, as well as the pottery and jewellery departments, are based at Blair Street. Abbeyhill Techbase is home to the weaving, textiles, printmaking, upholstery, dressmaking and machine knitting studios. As well as workshops, ECC offers classes for youth groups, private functions and one-to-one tuition. At ECC you can learn a new skill or hone your techniques to a fine art in comfortable and stimulating surroundings.

Name: Edinburgh Pallete, St Margarette's house
Summary: Today, Edinburgh Palette remains 100% occupied (with a waiting list for space) and houses community arts spaces, a theatre, rehearsal spaces, a cinema room, printmaking studio, ceramics studio & kilns, recording studio, martial arts dojo, library, swap shop, meeting rooms and more than 11000ft2 of gallery space. 200 studios with budding artists, crafters and community organisations.

Name: Edinburgh Printmakers
Adress: Castle Mills, 1 Dundee St, Edinburgh EH3 9FP

Name: Edinburgh Printmakers Gallery
Summary: Established in 1967 as the first open access studio in Britain, Edinburgh Printmakers is an organisation dedicated to the practice of fine art printmaking. We are committed to providing high quality, low cost printmaking facilities for artists.

Name: Edinburgh sculpture workshop
Summary: Events, Exhibitions, News, Opportunities, Residencies & Education is happening within the Building.

Name: Epoch 8
Summary: Epoch8 Gallery is organised and ran by local art students. We aim to engage the community by creating an inclusive platform that allows us to collaboratively share, create and respond with both artists and audience alike.

Name: Forest Café

Name: Fruitmarket Gallery
Summary: Contemporary art gallery, exhibitions, publications and events.

Name: Interview Room 11 - The Building
Summary: Founded in 2013, Interview Room 11 is an artist run gallery project. Originally located in Argyle House as a part of the FC+ Studios, we then moved to occupy space in Ocean Terminal, taking on a very different context in a large retail complex. We are currently reconfiguring our exhibition model, moving away from space-based programme towards utilising temporary spaces and digital platforms. IR11 also runs an artist studios, 'The Building', in Muirhouse, Edinburgh.

Our efforts are currently invested in the provision of affordable studio spaces for early career artists. In the near future, we hope to expand our remit to include regular events, sustainable fabrication facilities and community outreach initiatives.

Name: City observatory
Summary: Edinburgh's City Observatory, also known as the Playfair Observatory, is a fascinating place, where the optimism and excitement of early scientific advances can still be felt.Inspired by a Greek temple of the Four Winds, the Observatory was designed by William Henry Playfair in 1818. Established in 1984, Collective has long supported new work by artists who are at a pivotal stage in their development. In November 2018, we opened our new home on Calton Hill, featuring the restored City Observatory, City Dome, and a purpose-built exhibition space. Our programme of exhibitions, walks, and events will present contemporary art in all its diversity. We will provide artists with the opportunity to make new work and audiences the chance to see it here first. By inspiring, engaging with, and learning from the people and groups around us, we aim to contribute to local, national, and international conversations.
